Let X be a compact Kähler variety (for example, smooth and projective). By the holomorphic Poincaré lemma, the de Rham complex \Omega _X^\bullet is a resolution of the constant sheaf \mathbb {C}. We thus have an isomorphism () \operatorname {H}^\bullet (X,\mathbb {C}) \sim \operatorname {\mathbb {H}}^\bullet (X,\Omega _X^\bullet ) and the stupid filtration on \Omega _X^\bullet () defines the hypercohomology spectral sequence
467hodge-theory-ii-2.2.1.1hodge-theory-ii-2.2.1.1.xmlEquation2.2.1.1hodge-theory-ii-2.2.1 E_1^{pq} = \operatorname {H}^q(X,\Omega _X^q) \Rightarrow \operatorname {H}^{p+q}(X,\mathbb {C}) \tag{2.2.1.1}
which abuts to the Hodge filtration of \operatorname {H}^\bullet (X,\mathbb {C}).

We now prove (iii).
      If f\colon  X\to  S is smooth and projective, then there exists a dense Zariski open subset U of S along with a commutative diagram


    \usepackage {amsmath}
    \usepackage {amssymb}
    \usepackage {tikz-cd}
  \begin {tikzcd}
        X' \ar [rr,"p"] \ar [dr,swap,"f'"]
        && X|U \ar [dl,"f|U"]
      \\& U
      \end {tikzcd}

      with f' smooth and projective, and p birational and surjective (by applying Chow's lemma and the resolution of singularities to the generic fibre of f).
      The restriction map
               p^*\colon  (\mathrm {R} f_*\mathbb {Q})|U \to  \mathrm {R} f'_*\mathbb {Q}       
      is thus a direct injection of continuous families of Hodge structures, with left inverse given by the Gysin morphism p_!, whence the algebraicity of \mathrm {R} f_*\mathbb {Q}.
